## The Adversaryâ€™s Perspective
Your friend in cyberwar thinks in tactical exploits:
* Find a vulnerability (e.g., SQLi, RCE).
* Escalate privileges (e.g., sudo, token theft).
* Move laterally (e.g., Pass-the-Hash).
* Exfiltrate data (e.g., rclone, DNS tunneling).

Your Trustfile breaks this chain at every step:

| Attack Phase         | Their Tool             | Your Countermeasure                                   | Result                 |
|----------------------|------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|------------------------|
| Reconnaissance       | Nmap, Shodan           | DNS ZoneMD + transparency logs expose scanning.       | Detected immediately.  |
| Initial Access       | Phishing, zero-days    | Capability-based auth + LEAN4-proven policies.        | No exploit primitives. |
| Privilege Escalation | Mimikatz, CVE-202X-XXXX | PHP-Aegis + Sanctify block unsafe functions.          | No escalation possible. |
| Lateral Movement     | Pass-the-Hash, RDP     | SDP (CAdRE Router) + OCAP tokens.                     | No movement allowed.   |
| Data Exfiltration    | rclone, DNS tunneling  | Consent-Aware HTTP + transparency logs.               | Blocked by default.    |
| Persistence          | Cron jobs, web shells  | Ephemeral capabilities + immutable logs.              | No persistence possible. |

